          "Within ten years of taking the throne, King Aegas reformed the realm and established walled towns to protect against future attacks. Conversion from the old Vindammari faiths proved troublesome in the rural hinterlands. In the summer of 860CR, Aegas summoned the clerics of the realm, both Covenant and unconverted, to the ancient ruins at Awen, where Elves had first learned to speak with the spirits. There, theological compromises brought the rival churches together. A senior cleric, the Awensere, was made chief advisor to the king. The old Vindammari gods were recognised as Divines of Aeladh. The church was unified.",
          "The first Awensere was nominated by the Mother herself. But as she travelled back from the Council of Awen, her cavalcade was ambushed by assassins. She was slain without a trace left behind, her corpse consumed by flame. This is known as the Third Sin. King Aegas had four sons and lived over 120 years — more evidence of his divine inheritance. But in 930CR, his youngest son Urossa poisoned him and slew the eldest son, sparking a bitter civil war that fractured the old Aegir kingdom beyond reunification. As nobles went to war, much of the countryside was left in the hands of clerics, who brought stability and helped their lands evade the worst atrocities. When war was done, the Covenant remained intact to unite the people where kings could not.",
