          "The Covenant has become embedded in rural, civic, and noble societies in Forodain. It guides the law, social behaviour, and morality during peacetime, as well as the conduct and legitimacy of war. Its clerics conduct marriages among all classes, from king and earl down to villeins and slaves. Its high clerics arbitrate disputes, and the Awensere is the guarantor of peace between many kings of the north.",
          "In 1384CR, King Ulric of Heath died without an heir, and the rival claims of Duke Howland and the young prince Edric tore the land apart. The Covenant preached its neutrality, and Edric was eventually anointed in 1388CR with the support of the church. Shortly after, raids by orcs from the south escalated into a full Kainan invasion. In 1389CR, the Black Hand banner of Baalphegor was seen amidst a host that devastated the land, feasting on the harvest and driving starving refugees before them. The Covenant faced its greatest test in generations.",
          "With allies from Hart, Anglass, and even the reclusive Vallasaari clans, the alliance trapped the Kainan host in a valley. King Edric's army routed the orcs, but victory was bitter — the king returned ill and has since retreated from public life. The land of Heath remains badly disfigured by both the civil strife and the Kainan invasion. Rival lords use the king's absence to settle old scores, while the people look to the church for aid and succour.",
          "By the present day of 1422CR, the Covenant sits in the midst of a delicate balance of competing powers. If war looms, the Covenant will do all it can to forestall it, lest the war-weary people, and the kingdom itself, fall in the conflict.",
